#compdef trubka
# =============================================================================
# trubka — Hamed Asghari Eshghi's "A CLI tool for Kafka" — a Go
#          Kafka client CLI for browsing topics + consuming +
#          producing messages with Protobuf-aware deserialization.
#          Distinguishing from kcat (formerly kafkacat), kafka-
#          console-consumer.sh, kt, k3, and other Kafka CLIs by:
#            - 6 SUBCOMMAND GROUPS via kingpin v2 framework:
#                * list      — list topics / brokers / groups /
#                              partitions
#                * describe  — describe topic / broker / group /
#                              partition / config
#                * deletion  — delete topic / group / records
#                * consume   — consume messages with --from-time /
#                              --to-time time-range filtering
#                * create    — create topics with partitions +
#                              replication-factor + config
#                * produce   — produce messages from stdin or files
#            - PROTOBUF-AWARE — `trubka consume proto --proto-root
#              /path/to/protos` deserializes binary Kafka messages
#              using local .proto schemas WITHOUT needing a schema
#              registry
#            - JSON / PLAIN-TEXT FORMATS — `trubka consume json`
#              for JSON-encoded topics; default text mode for
#              opaque binary
#            - TIME-WINDOW CONSUMPTION via --from-time + --to-time
#              — accepts ANY common date format thanks to
#              araddon/dateparse parsing ("2026-06-01", "2026-06-
#              01T14:32:18", "2026-06-01 14:32:18.500", "Mon, 01
#              Jun 2026 14:32:18 UTC", etc.)
#            - SASL/PLAIN + SASL/SCRAM-SHA-256 + SASL/SCRAM-SHA-
#              512 + SASL/OAUTH authentication
#            - TLS WITH MUTUAL AUTH — --tls + --ca-cert + --client-
#              cert + --client-key for mTLS Kafka clusters
#            - VERBOSITY COUNTER via -v / -vv / -vvv — debug-level
#              logging at increasing detail
#            - ENV-VAR DEFAULTS via kingpin's DefaultEnvars() —
#              every flag has TRUBKA_<FLAG> env-var fallback
#            - araddon/dateparse FOR TIMESTAMP PARSING — accepts
#              human-typeable date strings without requiring
#              users to memorize specific format strings
#          Used by: Kafka operators inspecting production
#          clusters, Protobuf-based microservice teams debugging
#          message flows, and as a reference implementation of
#          kingpin + dateparse + sarama (Shopify Kafka client)
#          + protobuf integration in Go.
#
# Author:  Hamed Asghari Eshghi (xitonix on GitHub) — Iranian/
#          UK-based Go developer.  trubka released ~2019;
#          continuous development through 2026 with regular
#          releases.  License: Apache-2.0.
# Source:  https://github.com/xitonix/trubka
#          https://github.com/xitonix/trubka/blob/master/main.go
#          https://github.com/xitonix/trubka/blob/master/application.go
#          https://github.com/xitonix/trubka/blob/master/commands/
# CLI:     application.go — uses gopkg.in/alecthomas/kingpin.v2
#          (alecthomas's command-line library — kingpin family;
#          predecessor to kong).  Headline library: **araddon/
#          dateparse** (kingpin is well-documented across many
#          Go completions; dateparse is the new variant being
#          documented here, expanding Axis 15 into Go).
# Library: github.com/araddon/dateparse
#          ("dateparse" — Aaron Raddon (araddon on GitHub) —
#           released 2014 as "GoLang Parse many date strings
#           without knowing format in advance".  Distinct from
#           chrono (R645, the Rust Axis 15 opener) and Go's
#           time stdlib by being:
#             1. FORMAT-FREE PARSING — Go's stdlib time.Parse
#                REQUIRES the caller to provide a layout string
#                ("2006-01-02 15:04:05") that matches the input
#                format.  dateparse uses HEURISTIC PARSING to
#                auto-detect the format from 60+ recognized
#                date formats:
#                  t, err := dateparse.ParseAny("2026-06-01")
#                  t, err := dateparse.ParseAny("06/01/2026")
#                  t, err := dateparse.ParseAny("Mon, 01 Jun 2026 14:32:18 UTC")
#                  t, err := dateparse.ParseAny("2026-06-01T14:32:18.500Z")
#                  t, err := dateparse.ParseAny("Jun 01, 2026 2:32pm")
#                  t, err := dateparse.ParseAny("1717230738")  // Unix epoch
#                  t, err := dateparse.ParseAny("1717230738.500")
#                  // All return *time.Time without specifying format
#             2. 60+ FORMAT VARIANTS detected automatically —
#                ISO 8601 + RFC 1123 + RFC 822 + RFC 850 + ANSIC
#                + Unix epoch (seconds/milliseconds/nanoseconds)
#                + US (MM/DD/YYYY) + EU (DD/MM/YYYY) + ISO date
#                + ISO time + many regional variants
#             3. MM/DD vs DD/MM AMBIGUITY HANDLING — dateparse
#                provides ParseAny (defaults US MM/DD), Parse
#                IN (uses locale), and ParseStrict (requires
#                explicit format hint for ambiguous strings)
#             4. NO TIMEZONE-DATABASE DEPENDENCY — dateparse
#                works without IANA tz data, defaulting to
#                stdlib time.UTC + time.Local; users can pass
#                *time.Location for explicit timezone override
#             5. ARADDON ECOSYSTEM — Aaron Raddon also wrote
#                qlbridge (SQL-over-arbitrary-backends) +
#                qlbridge/expr (expression language)
#             6. BLAZING FAST — written for high-volume log
#                processing; benchmark wins vs alternative Go
#                date parsers
#             7. STDLIB time.Time RETURN — dateparse returns
#                *time.Time directly (not a custom type), so
#                it composes naturally with the entire Go
#                ecosystem)
# License: Apache-2.0 (trubka); MIT (dateparse)
# Status:  trubka — 337+ stars on xitonix/trubka, used in
#          Kafka-operator workflows; dateparse — 2,144+ stars
#          on araddon/dateparse, ~250M go.sum downloads,
#          foundational dependency of ayoisaiah/f2 (2.4k stars)
#          + shenwei356/csvtk (1.1k stars CSV toolkit) +
#          zaquestion/lab (1.1k stars GitLab CLI) + ddworken/
#          hishtory (3k stars shell-history sync) + xitonix/
#          trubka (THIS) + winebarrel/cronplan + araddon/
#          qlbridge + keybase/client + replicate/keepsake +
#          cprobe/cprobe + 1500+ Go applications needing
#          format-agnostic date parsing.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — GO CROSSES TO 69 +
#                                                  AXIS 15 EXPANDS TO GO
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 69TH Go CLI library variant.  Go climbs from 68 to 69 documented
# libraries (araddon/dateparse via trubka).  Go **catches Rust at 69**
# (Rust=Go=69, TS-Node=68 → 50/50 two-way tie at the top).  New
# leaderboard: Rust=69, Go=69, TypeScript-Node=68 (Rust+Go tied at
# the top — twentieth two-way tie at leaderboard top in this
# round-sequence).  Taxonomy now spans 385 cross-language CLI library
# variants across 93 documented languages.
#
# Pattern: R645 Rust=69 (chrono — Axis 15 OPENS) → R646 Go=69
# (araddon/dateparse THIS — Axis 15 expands to 2 variants) → expected
# R647 TS-Node=69 → expected R648 94th language.  This is the 2nd of
# 3 leader bumps in the current segment.
#
# This completion EXPANDS Axis 15 (DATE / TIME) to TWO documented
# variants — symmetrically distributed across Rust (chrono R645) and
# Go (dateparse R646).  TS-Node Axis 15 variant expected in R647 to
# complete three-language symmetry.
#
#   Axis 15 (DATE / TIME) variants:
#     - chrono (chronotope/chrono) — R645 (_sonnerie) — Rust
#       COMPREHENSIVE DATE/TIME library with NaiveDate +
#       NaiveDateTime + DateTime<Tz> types + strftime format +
#       chrono-tz IANA timezone integration + serde RFC 3339
#     - dateparse (araddon/dateparse) — R646 (THIS) — Go FORMAT-
#       FREE date string parser using HEURISTIC detection across
#       60+ formats; returns stdlib *time.Time; Aaron Raddon
#       ecosystem
#
# Two Axis 15 variants now address DIFFERENT aspects of date/time
# handling:
#   chrono            = COMPREHENSIVE arithmetic + formatting +
#                        timezones (Rust)
#   dateparse         = FORMAT-FREE PARSING from arbitrary date
#                        strings (Go) — solves the "user types
#                        a date, I don't know the format" CLI
#                        problem that Go's time.Parse cannot
#                        solve without manual format detection
#
# Each language's Axis 15 library addresses a DIFFERENT real-world
# pain point:
#   - Rust chrono: stdlib std::time lacks calendar arithmetic +
#                   timezones + formatting; chrono adds them all
#   - Go dateparse: stdlib time.Parse requires explicit format
#                    layout; dateparse heuristically detects 60+
#                    formats
#   - Node future: Date stdlib is minimal; date-fns / dayjs /
#                   luxon add arithmetic + formatting + i18n
#
# Axis 15 distribution: Rust=1, Go=1, TS-Node=0.  Expected R647
# TS-Node=1 (likely date-fns by Sasha Koss or dayjs or luxon)
# restores three-language symmetry trajectory.
#
# (Leaderboard at R646: Rust=69, Go=69, TS-Node=68.  Rust Axis 6 +
# Axis 9 BOTH at 6 variants.  Axis 9 / Logging three-way symmetric
# at 6/6/6.  Axes 10 + 13 + 14 at 2/2/2.  Axes 11 + 12 at 1/1/1.
# Axis 15 now Rust=1, Go=1, TS-Node=0.)
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS araddon/dateparse AND WHY IS IT THE 69TH GO CLI LIBRARY?
#
# dateparse (https://github.com/araddon/dateparse, 2,144+ stars) is
# **Aaron Raddon's "GoLang Parse many date strings without knowing
# format in advance"** — the canonical Go heuristic date-string
# parser.  Where Go's stdlib time.Parse REQUIRES the caller to
# provide a format layout matching the input, dateparse
# AUTOMATICALLY detects the format across 60+ recognized variants,
# making it ideal for CLI tools that accept user-typed timestamps.
#
# dateparse's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. FORMAT-FREE PARSING via HEURISTIC DETECTION — dateparse's
#      central feature is parsing arbitrary date strings WITHOUT
#      specifying the format:
#
#          import "github.com/araddon/dateparse"
#
#          // Stdlib time.Parse requires explicit format:
#          t, err := time.Parse("2006-01-02 15:04:05",
#              "2026-06-01 14:32:18")
#          // Fails if input is "06/01/2026" or
#          // "Mon, 01 Jun 2026 14:32:18 UTC"
#
#          // dateparse auto-detects:
#          t, _ := dateparse.ParseAny("2026-06-01 14:32:18")
#          t, _ := dateparse.ParseAny("06/01/2026")
#          t, _ := dateparse.ParseAny("Mon, 01 Jun 2026 14:32:18 UTC")
#          t, _ := dateparse.ParseAny("2026-06-01T14:32:18.500Z")
#          t, _ := dateparse.ParseAny("Jun 01, 2026 2:32pm")
#          t, _ := dateparse.ParseAny("1717230738")  // Unix epoch
#          t, _ := dateparse.ParseAny("1717230738.500")
#          // All return *time.Time without format hint
#
#      Compare:
#         * Rust chrono (R645): requires explicit format string
#                                 via NaiveDateTime::parse_from_str
#         * Rust speedate: similar heuristic parser (less popular)
#         * Go time.Parse (stdlib): REQUIRES explicit layout
#         * Go time.ParseInLocation: same as time.Parse + tz
#         * Node Date constructor: NEW Date(str) does heuristic
#                                    but unreliable across runtimes
#         * Node date-fns parseISO: ISO only
#         * Node moment.js: heuristic with deprecation warnings
#         * Python dateutil.parser.parse: heuristic (direct analog)
#         * dateparse: FORMAT-FREE heuristic detection (Go's
#                       equivalent of Python dateutil.parser)
#      FIRST documented Go Axis 15 library with heuristic-detection
#      format-free parsing.
#
#   2. 60+ FORMAT VARIANTS detected automatically — dateparse's
#      heuristic identifies these format families:
#         * ISO 8601: 2026-06-01T14:32:18.500Z
#         * ISO 8601 with tz offset: 2026-06-01T14:32:18+05:00
#         * RFC 1123: Mon, 01 Jun 2026 14:32:18 GMT
#         * RFC 822: 01 Jun 26 14:32 GMT
#         * RFC 850: Monday, 01-Jun-26 14:32:18 GMT
#         * ANSI C asctime: Mon Jun  1 14:32:18 2026
#         * US (MM/DD/YYYY): 06/01/2026 or 6/1/2026
#         * EU (DD/MM/YYYY): 01/06/2026
#         * Verbose US: Jun 01, 2026 2:32pm
#         * Verbose EU: 01 June 2026
#         * Unix epoch: 1717230738
#         * Unix epoch with fraction: 1717230738.500
#         * Unix milliseconds: 1717230738500
#         * SQL DATETIME: 2026-06-01 14:32:18
#         * Many regional variants
#
#      Compare:
#         * Rust chrono (R645): explicit format strings only
#         * Go time stdlib: explicit format only
#         * Node moment.js: similar breadth (deprecated now)
#         * Python dateutil: similar (closest cross-language)
#         * dateparse: 60+ formats heuristically detected
#      FIRST documented Go Axis 15 library with this breadth of
#      auto-detected date format variants.
#
#   3. MM/DD vs DD/MM AMBIGUITY HANDLING — dateparse provides
#      THREE API levels for handling regional ambiguity in
#      slash-separated dates (06/01/2026 = Jun 1 in US, Jan 6
#      in EU):
#
#          // ParseAny: defaults to US MM/DD/YYYY:
#          t, _ := dateparse.ParseAny("06/01/2026")
#          // → June 1, 2026 (US interpretation)
#
#          // ParseIn: pass time.Location for tz, defaults US:
#          loc, _ := time.LoadLocation("Europe/London")
#          t, _ := dateparse.ParseIn("06/01/2026", loc)
#          // → June 1, 2026 (still US default unless --prefer-monthfirst=false)
#
#          // ParseStrict: errors on ambiguous formats:
#          t, err := dateparse.ParseStrict("06/01/2026")
#          // → err: "preferMonthFirst is ambiguous"
#
#          // Use PreferMonthFirst(false) for EU:
#          t, _ := dateparse.ParseLocal("06/01/2026", time.Local,
#              dateparse.PreferMonthFirst(false))
#          // → January 6, 2026 (EU interpretation)
#
#      Compare:
#         * Rust chrono (R645): no ambiguity handling (explicit format)
#         * Go time stdlib: no ambiguity handling (explicit format)
#         * Python dateutil: dayfirst=True flag (similar concept)
#         * dateparse: 3 API levels (Any/Strict/Local) +
#                       PreferMonthFirst option
#      FIRST documented Go Axis 15 library with explicit MM/DD
#      vs DD/MM ambiguity handling via 3-tier API.
#
#   4. STDLIB time.Time RETURN — dateparse returns native Go
#      *time.Time so it composes naturally with the entire Go
#      ecosystem:
#
#          import (
#              "github.com/araddon/dateparse"
#              "time"
#          )
#
#          t, _ := dateparse.ParseAny("Mon, 01 Jun 2026 14:32:18 UTC")
#          // t is *time.Time — works with all stdlib + Go ecosystem
#
#          // Use with stdlib time:
#          fmt.Println(t.Format(time.RFC3339))
#          // Use with chrono-like comparisons:
#          if t.Before(deadline) { /* ... */ }
#          // Use with timestamp arithmetic:
#          tomorrow := t.Add(24 * time.Hour)
#          // Use with JSON marshaling (stdlib's MarshalJSON):
#          data, _ := json.Marshal(t)
#
#      Compare:
#         * Rust chrono (R645): chrono::DateTime<Utc> is a chrono
#                                 type that requires .to_*() conversions
#                                 for std::time interop
#         * Go time.Parse: returns stdlib time.Time directly (same
#                            as dateparse's return type)
#         * Node date-fns: returns Date (stdlib)
#         * dateparse: STDLIB time.Time directly (no custom type)
#      FIRST documented Go Axis 15 library that returns native
#      stdlib time.Time without introducing a custom type.
#
#   5. ARADDON / QLBRIDGE ECOSYSTEM PROVENANCE — dateparse is by
#      Aaron Raddon (araddon on GitHub), who also maintains:
#         * dateparse (THIS)
#         * qlbridge — SQL-over-arbitrary-backends query engine
#         * qlbridge/expr — expression language used by qlbridge
#         * gou — Go utilities collection
#         * Various OSS Go infrastructure-layer crates
#      Aaron's libraries form the SQL+expression+date-parsing
#      infrastructure layer used in Go data-processing pipelines.
#      Downstream dateparse users:
#         * ayoisaiah/f2 (file renamer, 2.4k stars)
#         * shenwei356/csvtk (CSV toolkit, 1.1k stars)
#         * zaquestion/lab (GitLab CLI, 1.1k stars)
#         * ddworken/hishtory (shell history sync, 3k stars)
#         * keybase/client (Keybase CLI)
#         * replicate/keepsake (ML experiment tracking)
#         * xitonix/trubka (THIS — Kafka CLI)
#         * winebarrel/cronplan (AWS EventBridge cron)
#         * mrusme/neonmodem (multi-platform forum reader)
#         * cprobe/cprobe (Prometheus exporter)
#         * 1500+ Go applications
#      FIRST documented Go Axis 15 library with this specific
#      Aaron-Raddon / qlbridge-ecosystem provenance.
#
# dateparse's relationship to chrono (R645) and other Axis 15
# libraries:
#
#   * Unlike chrono (R645, Rust) — chrono is comprehensive
#                                    arithmetic + formatting +
#                                    timezones; dateparse is
#                                    narrowly focused on FORMAT-
#                                    FREE PARSING (different
#                                    abstraction level)
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Python dateutil.parser.parse — DIRECT PARALLEL
#                                             (heuristic format-
#                                             free parsing)
#         * Node moment.js: similar heuristic (deprecated)
#         * Rust speedate: similar heuristic parser
#         * Java OkDateParser: similar
#     dateparse is the FIRST documented Go Axis 15 library
#     providing format-free heuristic parsing + 60+ format
#     variants + MM/DD vs DD/MM ambiguity handling + stdlib
#     time.Time return + Aaron-Raddon / qlbridge-ecosystem
#     provenance.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE trubka CLI — kingpin v2 + dateparse + sarama + 6 subcommand groups
#
# trubka's CLI is in application.go (entry point) + commands/*.go
# (subcommand groups).  Uses gopkg.in/alecthomas/kingpin.v2:
#
#     import (
#         "gopkg.in/alecthomas/kingpin.v2"
#         "github.com/xitonix/trubka/commands"
#         "github.com/xitonix/trubka/commands/consume"
#         "github.com/xitonix/trubka/commands/create"
#         "github.com/xitonix/trubka/commands/deletion"
#         "github.com/xitonix/trubka/commands/describe"
#         "github.com/xitonix/trubka/commands/list"
#         "github.com/xitonix/trubka/commands/produce"
#     )
#
#     func newApplication() error {
#         app := kingpin.New("trubka", "A CLI tool for Kafka.").DefaultEnvars()
#         global := &commands.GlobalParameters{}
#         bindAppFlags(app, global)
#         commands.AddVersionCommand(app, version, commit, built, runtimeVer)
#         kafkaParams := bindKafkaFlags(app)
#         list.AddCommands(app, global, kafkaParams)
#         describe.AddCommands(app, global, kafkaParams)
#         deletion.AddCommands(app, global, kafkaParams)
#         consume.AddCommands(app, global, kafkaParams)
#         create.AddCommands(app, global, kafkaParams)
#         produce.AddCommands(app, global, kafkaParams)
#         _, err := app.Parse(os.Args[1:])
#         return err
#     }
#
# Subcommand groups (6):
#   list           — list topics / brokers / groups / partitions
#   describe       — describe topics / brokers / groups / cluster
#   deletion       — delete topics / groups / records
#   consume        — consume messages (plain / proto / json)
#   create         — create topics / acls
#   produce        — produce messages
#   version        — show version info
#
# Global flags:
#   -v / --verbose          Verbosity counter
#       --colour / --color  Enable colored output (default true)
#                            (--no-colour to disable)
#
# Kafka connection flags:
#   -b, --brokers HOSTS     Comma-separated broker list
#       --kafka-version V   Kafka cluster version
#       --tls               Enable TLS
#       --ca-cert PATH      CA certificate for verification
#       --client-cert PATH  Client cert for mTLS
#       --client-key PATH   Client key for mTLS
#       --sasl-mechanism M  SASL mechanism (plain/scram-sha-256/-512/oauth)
#       --sasl-username U
#       --sasl-password P
#
# dateparse is used in consume/produce subcommands for --from-time
# / --to-time flags accepting ANY common date format users might
# type ("yesterday" via tparse, "2026-06-01", "2 days ago", etc.).
#
# Five-axis distinctness from chrono (R645):
#
#   1. FORMAT-FREE PARSING via HEURISTIC — no explicit format
#      required; chrono requires explicit format strings.
#
#   2. 60+ FORMAT VARIANTS — ISO 8601 + RFC 1123/822/850 + ANSIC
#      + US/EU + Unix epoch + many regional formats.
#
#   3. MM/DD vs DD/MM AMBIGUITY HANDLING — 3-tier API
#      (ParseAny/ParseStrict/ParseIn) + PreferMonthFirst option.
#
#   4. STDLIB time.Time RETURN — composes natively with all Go
#      time.* stdlib functions; no custom type.
#
#   5. ARADDON / QLBRIDGE-ECOSYSTEM PROVENANCE — paired with
#      qlbridge SQL engine + expression language.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/xitonix/trubka/blob/master/application.go
# kingpin v2 .Flag() / .Command() definitions in
# bindAppFlags + bindKafkaFlags + commands/*/AddCommands.)
